If you're looking to turn your terminal into a playground for your Vim muscle memory, you're in the right place. To switch your current Bash session to vi mode, just run:

Bash
set -o vi
Quick Tips for Bash Vi Mode
Once you run that command, your shell will behave a lot like the editor. By default, you start in Insert mode.

Hit ESC: Switches you to Command mode.

Move around: Use h, j, k, l to navigate your command history and line text.

Edit: Use x to delete characters, dw to delete words, or dd to clear the whole line.

Search: Use / to search through your command history.

Back to typing: Press i or a to return to Insert mode.

How to make it permanent
If you don't want to type that every time you open a terminal (and who would?), you should add it to your configuration file.

Open your ~/.bashrc file in your favorite editor.

Add set -o vi to the bottom of the file.

Save and restart your terminal or run source ~/.bashrc.

Note: If you ever want to switch back to the default Emacs-style shortcuts (like Ctrl+A to go to the start of the line), just run set -o emacs.

