Remember: these work while you are in Command mode (after hitting ESC).

1. Navigating Like a Pro
w / b: Jump forward or backward by one word.

W / B: Jump forward/backward by a space-separated word (useful for skipping over complex file paths).

0 (zero): Jump to the very beginning of the line.

$: Jump to the very end of the line.

^: Jump to the first non-white-space character.

2. The "Big" History Search
While k and j move you up and down one line at a time, these are faster for finding that command you ran ten minutes ago:

/string: Search backward through history for "string". Hit n to find the next match.

?string: Search forward through history (if you've already moved back a few steps).

G: Jump to the very last command in your history.

#: Adds a # to the start of your current line and "saves" it to history without executing it. Great for pausing a long command to do something else first.

3. Editing Shortcuts
cc: Clear the entire line and go straight into Insert mode.

C (Shift + C): Delete everything from the cursor to the end of the line and enter Insert mode.

r: Replace a single character under the cursor without entering Insert mode.

v: The Nuclear Option. This opens your current command line in your actual $EDITOR (usually full Vim). When you save and exit the editor, Bash executes whatever you wrote.

