To make your terminal feel truly professional, you can customize the Vi Mode Indicator. Instead of a generic (ins), you can use custom symbols or colors to tell you exactly where you are.

This is done by setting the vi-ins-mode-string and vi-cmd-mode-string variables in your .inputrc file.

Step 1: Edit your .inputrc
Open (or create) the file ~/.inputrc and add these lines:

Bash
# Enable the mode indicator
set show-mode-in-prompt on

# Customize the symbols (you can use Unicode or plain text)
set vi-ins-mode-string "\1\e[32m\2(ins)\1\e[0m\2 "
set vi-cmd-mode-string "\1\e[31m\2(cmd)\1\e[0m\2 "
What that code does:
\1\e[32m\2: This is a Bash escape code that turns the text Green for Insert mode.

\1\e[31m\2: This turns the text Red for Command mode.

\1\e[0m\2: This resets the color back to normal so your actual prompt doesn't stay red or green.

Step 2: Refresh your shell
After saving the file, you need to tell your shell to reload the settings. Run:

Bash
bind -f ~/.inputrc
Now, when you hit ESC, your prompt will instantly swap from a green (ins) to a red (cmd). It's a lifesaver for avoiding those moments where you start typing a command only to realize you just deleted three lines of history because you were still in Command mode.

Visual Guide to Bash Vi Workflow
Mode	Visual Indicator (Customized)	Primary Function
Insert	(ins) (Green)	Typing your commands normally.
Command	(cmd) (Red)	Navigating, deleting, and searching history.
One last "hidden" gem: If you ever get stuck in a massive command and want to clear the whole line and start over without saving it to history, just hit ESC then S (capital S). It wipes the line and puts you back in Insert mode instantly.

