Here is the "scorched earth" fix to get your Arch/Ghostty/Tmux stack snappy and clean.

1. Kill the ".inputrc" Text
Since you see (ins) or (cmd), that's coming from your ~/.inputrc. It’s overriding Starship's cleaner look.

Open ~/.inputrc.

Remove or comment out set show-mode-in-prompt on.

Save and run bind -f ~/.inputrc.

2. Fix the Tmux/Ghostty Lag
If set -sg escape-time 0 didn't work, it's likely because Ghostty (which is very fast) or your version of tmux needs the "wait" time to be even more explicit.

In your ~/.tmux.conf, add:

Bash
set -s escape-time 0
set -g status-interval 1
Crucial: You must kill the tmux server for this to fully take effect. Run tmux kill-server and then restart your session. Simply "sourcing" the config often fails to update the global server escape timer.

3. The "Bleeding Edge" Bash Fix
Since Starship's vimcmd_symbol is notoriously finicky in Bash, most Arch users on Hyprland use a small script snippet to force the prompt to redraw.

Add this to your ~/.bashrc:

Bash
# Force Starship to update the character symbol on mode change
function _update_ps1() {
    PS1="$(starship prompt --terminal-width="$COLUMNS" --keymap="${KEYMAP:-default}")"
}

# Bind ESC to switch mode AND redraw the prompt
bind -m vi-insert 'set keymap vi-command'
bind -m vi-command 'set keymap vi-insert'
4. Why Starship isn't changing the symbol
In Bash, Starship relies on the $STARSHIP_KEYMAP or $KEYMAP variable. If those aren't being updated by the shell, Starship assumes you're always in "Insert" mode.

If you want the absolute "best" experience on Arch, many users switch from Bash to Zsh or Fish. Those shells have "Hooks" that tell Starship exactly when the mode changes, making the vimcmd_symbol work natively without all these hacks.

